## Best Practices

### Always List Before Acting
Every "action" tool has a corresponding "list" tool. Always list first to discover valid names and current states. Tool names are case-insensitive in lookups.

### Check Application State
Applications have states: `Stopped`, `Starting`, `Started`, `Stopping`. Do not start an already running app or stop an already stopped one -- the tools will return informative messages rather than errors, but it wastes a call.

### Use `all` Parameter for Batch Operations
`start_application`, `stop_application`, and `build_application` accept `all: true` to operate on all items at once. Use this instead of calling the tool repeatedly for each app.

### Respect Timeouts
`run_task` and `run_custom_command` accept `timeout_seconds` (default: 300). For long operations (large builds, npm install, Docker pulls), increase this value. If a timeout occurs, the operation may still be running in the background.

### Read Logs for Debugging
When `run_task` or `run_custom_command` fails, the response includes `logs` with the full stdout/stderr output. Read these logs before asking the user what went wrong.

### Custom Command Targets
Custom commands have `triggerTargets` (where the command appears in the UI) and `executionTargets` (which items it runs on). When calling `run_custom_command`:
- If `target_type` is omitted, the command runs at solution level
- For `HelmChartsRoot` and `SolutionRunnerRoot`, no `target_name` is needed
- For all other target types, `target_name` is required

### Monitor Filtering
All monitor tools (`get_logs`, `get_exceptions`, `get_requests`, `get_events`) accept an optional `app` parameter. When debugging a specific service, always filter by app name to reduce noise.

### Profile Awareness
Most Solution Runner operations work on the **currently selected** run profile. Always verify or switch the active profile before performing operations if the solution has multiple profiles.

